WEEK 14 IP: PART 1 & 2

Joy Kiriba

1) Defining the question

a) Specifying the data analytic question

Use unsupervised learning techniques to get insights from the given data set to help create marketing strategies that would lead to the highest number of sales.

b) Defining the metric of success

``The project will be a success when we are able to create marketing strategies that lead to the highest number of sales.```

c) Understanding the context

You are a Data analyst at Carrefour Kenya and are currently undertaking a project that will inform the marketing department on the most relevant marketing strategies that will result in the highest no. of sales (total price including tax). Your project has been divided into four parts where you'll explore a recent marketing dataset by performing various unsupervised learning techniques and later providing recommendations based on your insights.

d) Recording the experimental design

The process will entail:

  • Define the question, the metric for success, the context, experimental design taken.

  • Read and explore the given dataset.

  • Define the appropriateness of the available data to answer the given question.

  • Find and deal with outliers, anomalies, and missing data within the dataset.

  • Perform univariate and bivariate analysis recording my observations.

  • Implement the solution.

  • Challenge the solution.

  • Follow up questions.

e) Data relevance

The dataset used can be found here:

[Marketing dataset] (http://bit.ly/CarreFourDataset)

Observations from univariate analysis

  • Females are more than males but only by 2.

  • When it comes to customer tpes, members are more than the normal customers but only by 2.

  • Most customers pay via EWallet followed by credit card and card

  • The goods with most sales are fashion accessories, electronic accessories and food and food and beverages.

  • Most data entries came from branch A followed by B and C.

  • The total and cogs columns are positively skewed with most of the values concentrated to the left of the graph.

Conclusion

  • Principal component analysis does a great job in dimensionality reduction as the first 3 Principal components, out of 7, explain 98% of the variance in the data.

  • Tax, cogs, gross income and total are the largest contributors to PC1.

  • Rating , unit price and quantity are largest contributors to PC2.

  • Unit price, quantity and rating are the highest contributors to PC3.

  • Feature selection gave 4 variables: Unit price, quantity, gross income and ratings infering that these 4 variables would suffice in creating an accurate predictive model leading to maximizing of sales made.

Recommendations.

  • I would recommed to use of the first 3 PCs in creation of a predictive model as they explain 98% of the variance in the data.

  • As seen from feature selection, the 4 most important variables are Unit price, quantity, gross income and ratings. The formulation of Marketing strategies could be based on these variables for the supermarket to achieve the highest sales.
